  "prompt": "How do jellyfish breath?",
  "response": "Jellyfish don't have specialized respiratory systems like lungs or gills found in more complex animals. Instead, they rely on diffusion to breathe. Their thin, gelatinous bodies are composed primarily of water and surrounded by a thin layer of cells through which oxygen can diffuse directly from the surrounding water. As water moves over the surface of their bodies, oxygen from the water diffuses through their skin and into their cells, while carbon dioxide and other metabolic waste products diffuse out into the water.\n\nThis method of respiration is effective because jellyfish are primarily composed of water and have a large surface area relative to their volume, which allows efficient gas exchange directly through their external surfaces.",
